import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

#  data
x = np.linspace(-np.pi, np.pi, 100)

# 
plt.plot(x, cos_x, color = "blue", linewidth = 3, linestyle = "-")
plt.plot(x, sin_x, color = "red", linewidth = 3, linestyle = "-")

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

#  data
x = np.linspace(-np.pi, np.pi, 100)
cos_x, sin_x = np.cos(x), np.sin(x)

# 
plt.plot(x, cos_x, color = "blue", linewidth = 3, linestyle = "-", label = "cos(x)")
plt.plot(x, sin_x, color = "red", linewidth = 3, linestyle = "-", label = "sin(x)")
plt.xlim(x.min()*1.2, x.max()*1.2)
plt.ylim(cos_x.min()*1.2, cos_x.max()*1.2)
plt.xticks([-np.pi, -np.pi/2, 0, np.pi/2, np.pi], ["$-\pi$", "$-\pi/2$", "$0$", "$\pi/2$", "$\pi$"])
plt.yticks([-1, 0, 1], ["$-1$", "$0$", "$+1$"])
ax = plt.gca() # get current axes
ax.spines['right'].set_color('none')
ax.spines['top'].set_color('none')
ax.spines['bottom'].set_position(('data', 0))
ax.spines['left'].set_position(('data', 0))
plt.legend(loc = 'upper left', frameon = False)

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

#  data
x = np.linspace(-np.pi, np.pi, 100)
cos_x, sin_x = np.cos(x), np.sin(x)

# 
plt.plot(x, cos_x, color = "blue", linewidth = 3, linestyle = "-", label = "cos(x)")
plt.plot(x, sin_x, color = "red", linewidth = 3, linestyle = "-", label = "sin(x)")
plt.xlim(x.min()*1.2, x.max()*1.2)
plt.ylim(cos_x.min()*1.2, cos_x.max()*1.2)
plt.xticks([-np.pi, -np.pi/2, 0, np.pi/2, np.pi], ["$-\pi$", "$-\pi/2$", "$0$", "$\pi/2$", "$\pi$"])
plt.yticks([-1, 0, 1], ["$-1$", "$0$", "$+1$"])
ax = plt.gca() # get current axes
ax.spines['right'].set_color('none')
ax.spines['top'].set_color('none')
ax.spines['bottom'].set_position(('data', 0))
ax.spines['left'].set_position(('data', 0))

# plt.bar()
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

N = 5
ice_cream_sales = np.random.randint(50, 100, size = 5)
ind = np.arange(1, N + 1)
width = 0.5
plt.bar(ind, ice_cream_sales, width, facecolor = 'g')
plt.title('Ice cream sales by flavor')
plt.xticks(ind, ['Matcha', 'Chocolate', 'Vanilla', 'Coco', 'Strawberry']), plt.yticks([])
# Annotations
for x, y in zip(ind, ice_cream_sales):
    plt.text(x, y + 2, '%i' % y, ha = 'center', va = 'bottom')
plt.ylim(0, ice_cream_sales.max() * 1.2)
ax = plt.gca()
ax.spines['right'].set_color('none')
ax.spines['top'].set_color('none')
ax.spines['left'].set_color('none')

3D 平面圖¶

  • 3D
  • from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D
In [29]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D

fig = plt.figure()
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')

u = np.arange(start = -5, stop = 5, step = 0.1)
x, y = np.meshgrid(u, u)
z = x**2 + y**2
surf = ax.plot_surface(x, y, z, rstride = 2, cstride = 2, cmap = plt.cm.coolwarm, linewidth = 0.5, antialiased = True)
fig.colorbar(surf)
plt.show()

Future of Visualization Tools¶

Quoted from Wes McKinney:

The Future of Visualization Tools?

Visualizations built on web technologies (that is, JavaScript-based) appear to be the inevitable future. Doubtlessly you have used many different kinds of static or interactive visualizations built in Flash or JavaScript over the years. New toolkits (such as d3.js and its numerous off-shoot projects) for building such displays are appearing all the time. In contrast, development in non web-based visualization has slowed significantly in recent years. This holds true of Python as well as other data analysis and statistical computing environments like R.

Future of Visualization Tools（2）¶

  • Writing Python:
    • Bokeh
    • Plotly
  • Writing JavaScript:
    • d3.js

作業¶

  • sign_fun() x
$$ sgn(x) = \begin{cases} -1 & \quad \text{if } x < 0\\ 0 & \quad \text{if } x = 0\\ 1 & \quad \text{if } x > 0\\ \end{cases} $$
  • sigmoid_fun() x
$$S(x) = \frac{1}{1 + e^{-x}}$$
  • Optional
  • subplot() (1, 2) Optional
